# Clean Code Standards

Follow *Clean Code: A Handbook of Agile Software Craftsmanship* (Robert C. Martin) for every task: reviews, refactors, new features, fixes, and docs that describe code behavior.

**Priority when rules conflict:** correctness and security first, then existing project conventions, then these rules.

## Names

- Use names that reveal intent; avoid abbreviations unless they are domain-standard.
- Prefer searchable, pronounceable names over clever or encoded ones (`m`, `data2`, `temp`).
- One word per concept across the codebase (e.g. don’t mix `fetch`, `retrieve`, `get` for the same idea).
- Classes/nouns, methods/verbs; booleans read as questions (`isVisible`, `hasPermission`).
- Keep names at the right level of abstraction; don’t leak implementation (`getUserIdsFromRedis` → `getActiveUserIds` at call sites).

## Functions

- Small, do one thing, at one level of abstraction.
- Prefer ≤3 parameters; use objects/options when more are needed.
- No hidden side effects; name must match behavior.
- Prefer exceptions over error codes for exceptional flow; don’t use exceptions for normal control flow.
- Avoid flag arguments (`render(true)`); split into named functions.
- Extract until names read like prose; delete dead code immediately.

## Comments

- Prefer expressive code over comments.
- Good comments: legal, intent, warning, public API docs — not apologies or commented-out code.
- Don’t let comments rot; update or remove when code changes.

## Formatting & Structure

- Be consistent with the file and project (indent, quotes, imports).
- Related code stays close; variables declared near first use.
- Vertical openness: separate concepts with blank lines; keep dense logic readable.
- Files and modules should feel like one cohesive idea.

## Objects, Data & Boundaries

- Hide implementation; expose behavior, not raw data shapes when a type can enforce invariants.
- Law of Demeter: don’t chain through strangers (`a.b().c().d()`).
- Wrap third-party APIs behind thin adapters the app owns.
- Learn and test at integration boundaries.

## Error Handling

- Use `try/catch` around operations that can fail; keep catch blocks focused.
- Don’t return `null`/`undefined` when a clearer pattern exists (empty result, `Option`, typed error).
- Provide context in errors/messages; fail fast at boundaries.
- Never swallow errors silently.

## Classes & Modules (SRP)

- Single Responsibility: one reason to change per module/class.
- High cohesion, low coupling; depend on abstractions where the project already does.
- Prefer composition over inheritance unless the framework requires otherwise.

## Tests

- F.I.R.S.T.: Fast, Independent, Repeatable, Self-validating, Timely.
- One logical behavior per test; descriptive names (`shouldRejectExpiredToken`).
- Arrange–Act–Assert; minimal setup; test public behavior, not implementation details.
- Tests are documentation — keep them as clean as production code.

## Code Smells — Refactor When You See

- Duplication, long functions/files, large classes, long parameter lists.
- Feature envy, inappropriate intimacy, switch statements duplicating across types.
- Dead code, speculative generality, magic numbers/strings (name constants).
- Comments explaining *what* instead of *why* the code can’t say itself.

## Craftsmanship (How to Work)

- Leave code cleaner than you found it (boy scout rule).
- Minimize diff scope: only change what the task needs.
- Match existing naming, types, folder layout, and patterns in the repo.
- No drive-by refactors unrelated to the request.
- When adding features, extend tests that prove behavior; don’t add trivial tests unless asked.

## TypeScript / React (this repo)

- Prefer explicit types at boundaries; infer locally when obvious.
- Components: presentational vs logic split when complexity grows; extract hooks for reusable behavior.
- Avoid `any`; use narrow types and guards at API edges.
- Side effects in effects/handlers only where needed; keep render paths pure.

## Review Checklist (before finishing)

- [ ] Names and functions read clearly without comments?
- [ ] Functions small, single-purpose, no surprise side effects?
- [ ] Errors handled with context, not swallowed?
- [ ] Duplication removed or justified?
- [ ] Change matches project style and smallest necessary scope?
